      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>5</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001P/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001P</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001P/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="sheaf condition using Lawvere–Tierney operators">sheaf condition using Lawvere–Tierney operators</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Knowing the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001N/" title="Grothendieck coverages and Lawvere–Tierney operators" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001N/" display-uri="algm-001N" type="local">correspondence</fr:link> of Grothendieck coverages on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> and Lawvere–Tierney operators on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {Psh}(\mathcal {C})]]></fr:tex>, we naturally want to rewrite the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf condition</fr:link> to use <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operators</fr:link> instead of <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverages</fr:link>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  Recall that the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf condition</fr:link> requires for every covering sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \hookrightarrow  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> that the composition <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), X) \to  \hom (S, X)]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism. We can reify this to a definition.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001R/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>algm-001R</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/algm-001R/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="local object">local object</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Given a class of arrows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>local object</html:strong> is an object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : A \to  B]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, the composition map <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\hom (B, X) \to  \hom (A, X)]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
  Now we just need to pick out the class of morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \hookrightarrow  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> using the Lawvere–Tierney operator <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>. Note that this operator does not necessarily live in a presheaf topos, so we must find a way to generalize this class of arrows to not necessarily representable presheaves. Since every presheaf is a colimit of representables, we can look at the corresponding colimit of morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname *{colim} S_i \hookrightarrow  \operatorname *{colim} \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i)]]></fr:tex>. A local object will satisfy
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {aligned}
    \hom (\operatorname *{colim}\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i), X) \cong  \lim \hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i), X) \quad  \\
    \xrightarrow {\sim } \lim \hom (S_i, X) \cong  \hom (\operatorname *{colim} S_i, X).
  \end {aligned}]]></fr:tex>
  Hence we can safely include these arrows into the class and still get the same concept of local objects. Now it’s illuminating to look at the characteristic maps. A sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \to  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> corresponds to a characteristic map in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), \Omega ) \cong  \Gamma (U, \Omega )]]></fr:tex>. Generalizing to an arbitrary presheaf expressed (canonically) as a colimit of representables, we need the image of every section to be a covering sieve.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001Q/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>algm-001Q</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/algm-001Q/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="dense subobject of a Lawvere–Tierney operator">dense subobject of a Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>, a subobject <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F \hookrightarrow  G]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>dense</html:strong> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G \to  \Omega  \xrightarrow {j} \Omega ]]></fr:tex> is the constant true. In terms of the corresponding <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J \hookrightarrow  \Omega ]]></fr:tex>, we need the pullback of it with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G \to  \Omega ]]></fr:tex> to be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\textrm {id} : G \to  G]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
  In terms of sieves, for every section <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s \in  \Gamma (U, G)]]></fr:tex>, the sieve of arrows on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> along whom the restriction of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> is in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> must be a covering sieve. We have arrived at the desired reformulation of the sheaf condition.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001S/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>algm-001S</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/algm-001S/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="sheaf of a Lawvere–Tierney operator">sheaf of a Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>, a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>sheaf</html:strong> is defined as a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>local object</html:strong>, i.e. a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001R/" title="local object" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001R/" display-uri="algm-001R" type="local">local object</fr:link> under the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001Q/" title="dense subobject of a Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001Q/" display-uri="algm-001Q" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-dense monomorphisms</fr:link>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>3</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001K/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001K</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001K/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="separation of presheaf">separation of presheaf</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Construction</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link>, the inclusion of <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">separated presheaves</fr:link> to presheaves has a left adjoint <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-)^{\operatorname {sep}}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>3</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    We define <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (U, P^{\operatorname {sep}})]]></fr:tex> to be a quotient of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (U, P)]]></fr:tex>. Two sections are considered the same if they are equal on a covering sieve. It is obvious that this is separated, and in a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  Q]]></fr:tex> to a separated presheaf, if two sections of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> are equal on a covering sieve, then their image will also be, and by separatedness they must be actually equal in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>3</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001I/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001I</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001I/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="sheaf condition in terms of plus construction">sheaf condition in terms of plus construction</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a presheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, the morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P^+]]></fr:tex> to its <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001E/" title="plus construction" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001E/" display-uri="algm-001E" type="local">plus construction</fr:link> is a monomorphism iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">separated</fr:link>, and it is an isomorphism iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf</fr:link>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>3</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001J/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001J</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001J/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="sheafification">sheafification</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p><html:strong>Sheafification</html:strong> is defined as the left adjoint of the inclusion from <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaves</fr:link> to the category of presheaves. Hence it freely constructs a sheaf from a presheaf.
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>3</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    We construct sheafification as <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001G/" title="iterated plus construction produces a sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001G/" display-uri="algm-001G" type="local">an iterated plus construction</fr:link>. This produces a functor. By <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001H/" title="universal property of plus construction" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001H/" display-uri="algm-001H" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001H/" display-uri="algm-001H" /></fr:link> we have a natural bijection
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\hom (P^{++}, F) \cong  \hom (P^+, F) \cong  \hom (P, F).]]></fr:tex>
    Hence it is indeed the left adjoint. Since the bijections are given by composition with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P^+]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+ \to  P^{++}]]></fr:tex>, we see that the unit of the adjunction is given by the composition <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P^{++}]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    Alternatively, using <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001K/" title="separation of presheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001K/" display-uri="algm-001K" type="local">Construction <fr:contextual-number uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001K/" display-uri="algm-001K" /></fr:link>, we may compose two adjunctions to first <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001K/" title="separation of presheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001K/" display-uri="algm-001K" type="local">separate</fr:link> the presheaf, and then perform the plus construction. By uniqueness of adjunction these two constructions are equivalent.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>3</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001H/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001H</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001H/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="universal property of plus construction">universal property of <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001E/" title="plus construction" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001E/" display-uri="algm-001E" type="local">plus construction</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any presheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> and sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, there is a natural bijection <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\hom (P, F) \cong  \hom (P^+, F)]]></fr:tex> given by composition with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta _P : P \to  P^+]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p><html:p>
  As a corollary of this and <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001G/" title="iterated plus construction produces a sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001G/" display-uri="algm-001G" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001G/" display-uri="algm-001G" /></fr:link>, when restricted to separated presheaves, it is left adjoint to the forgetful functor from sheaves to separated presheaves.
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>3</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    For every morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  F]]></fr:tex>, there is a unique way to extend the map to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> using the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf condition</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>. A section of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> consists of a matching family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_f]]></fr:tex>, and it is also the gluing of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta _P(s_f)]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>2</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001G/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001G</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001G/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="iterated plus construction produces a sheaf">iterated <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001E/" title="plus construction" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001E/" display-uri="algm-001E" type="local">plus construction</fr:link> produces a sheaf</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Given any presheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">separated presheaf</fr:link>, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is already separated, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf</fr:link>. Therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^{++}]]></fr:tex> is always a sheaf.
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>2</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    We first prove that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> is separated. Suppose there are two gluings of a set of descent data on a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">covering sieve</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then we have two sieves <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_1, S_2]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> with compatible families <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{1, f}, s_{2, f}]]></fr:tex>. Since they are gluings of the same descent data, the restriction along any morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : U \to  A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> would be equal. Hence there is a common refinement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g^* S_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g^* S_2]]></fr:tex> where the two families become equal. Expanding this, there is a covering sieve on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g \mathbin {\circ } h \in  S_1 \cap  S_2]]></fr:tex> for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h]]></fr:tex> in the sieve, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{1, g \mathbin {\circ } h} = s_{2, g \mathbin {\circ } h}]]></fr:tex>. But then by the axioms of a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g \mathbin {\circ } h]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h]]></fr:tex> in the said sieve and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g \in  S]]></fr:tex> also generates a covering sieve. Hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_2]]></fr:tex> are already equal on a covering subsieve, and so they are equal in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (A, P^+)]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    Let’s see why <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> is not necessarily a sheaf. To be a sheaf, we need to find a gluing for each compatible family. A <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001D/" title="descent data of presheaves" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001D/" display-uri="algm-001D" type="local">compatible family</fr:link> of local sections of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> is a family of covering sieves <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_f]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> for each morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : U \to  A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, and for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_f]]></fr:tex> a family of sections <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f, g} \in  \Gamma (V, P)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : V \to  U]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_f]]></fr:tex>. By the axioms of a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link>, the union <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigcup _{f \in  S} f \mathbin {\circ } S_f]]></fr:tex> is a sieve, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_f \subseteq  f^* (f \mathbin {\circ } S_f)]]></fr:tex>. (Warning: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \mathbin {\circ } S_f]]></fr:tex> is not a covering sieve itself.) So we are tempted to simply construct a glued section <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s']]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s'_{f \mathbin {\circ } g} = s_{f, g}]]></fr:tex>. Hence we need to prove <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f, g} = s_{f', g'}]]></fr:tex> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \mathbin {\circ } g = f' \mathbin {\circ } g']]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    Since the families <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f}]]></fr:tex> are compatible, given any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : V \to  U]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f, g \mathbin {\circ } r} = s_{f \mathbin {\circ } g, r}]]></fr:tex> for a family of arrows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> that generates a covering sieve on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex>. However we cannot necessarily take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r = \textrm {id}]]></fr:tex>, so this is not necessarily well-defined. Here is where the separatedness comes in. Notice that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f, g \mathbin {\circ } r} = s_{f \mathbin {\circ } g, r}]]></fr:tex> forms a compatible family over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> ranges over the covering sieve. And therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f, g}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{f \mathbin {\circ } g, \textrm {id}}]]></fr:tex> are both a gluing of the family. By separatedness, they must be equal. Hence our problem is solved.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
